    "body": "## Problem\n\n`importdescriptors` is documented as best-effort: each item in the batch either succeeds or returns its own error in `result[i].error`. In practice, a missing or malformed `\"timestamp\"` field breaks this contract — `GetImportTimestamp()` throws before `ProcessDescriptorImport`'s try/catch can catch it, aborting the whole RPC and discarding the result array. Items already committed to the wallet are left with no way for the caller to know which succeeded or failed.\n\nAll other validation failures (bad descriptor, unknown key, etc.) already land in `result[i].error` correctly. Timestamp validation was the odd one out.\n\nReported in #35181.\n\n## Solution\n\nWrap the `GetImportTimestamp` call in a `try/catch (const UniValue&)` block — the same catch type used inside `ProcessDescriptorImport`. On failure, push a `{success: false, error: ...}` object into `response` and `continue` to the next item, matching the per-item error contract.\n\nThe rescan loop re-calls `GetImportTimestamp` per item when composing the final response after a partial-rescan failure. It already guards already-errored items via `results.at(i).exists(\"error\")`, but that guard only fires when it appears as the first `||` operand. Swap the operands so already-errored items (including those caught above) short-circuit past the `GetImportTimestamp` call.",
